            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Well, that depends on what the function does -- it wasn't exactly well documented before...\r\n\r\nAt a guess (correct me if I misunderstand what it does), I'd expand on the functionality in the general docstring and then just distinguish between the _targets_  in the parameters. (It's important not to use two different words for the same thing...)\r\n\r\nMaybe something like\r\n```\r\nConverts a string of names of |keycodes| to different representations. By default, it returns a string with the internal representation of the actual keypress events, but it can also parse it into a table of base keys and modifiers.\r\n\r\n    Example: >lua\r\n        vim.g.mapleader = vim.keycode('<bs>')\r\n        print(vim.g.mapleader)\r\n        --- \"<80>kb\"\r\n        \r\n        vim.print(vim.keycode('<C-A><C-S-A>', { output = 'table' })\r\n        --- { <insert output here> }\r\n<\r\n```\r\n(@gpanders please correct the terminal terminology here)\r\n\r\nAnd any optional arguments should not be positional for future extensions, so make this `opts` with `opts.output: 'table'|'code'?` to leave the door open for future formats.\r\n\r\n(Naming TBD @justinmk)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
            "commit_id": "01674c97c49e14a055bea0e9a9d8a5a8556071e0",
            "created_at": "2026-04-06T09:36:30Z",
            "diff_hunk": "@@ -1329,10 +1329,14 @@ vim.keycode({str})                                             *vim.keycode()*\n <\n \n     Parameters: ~\n-      • {str}  (`string`) String to be converted.\n+      • {str}    (`string`) String to be converted.\n+      • {parse}  (`boolean`) Parse the keycode instead.",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/38636#discussion_r3038814728",
